[P]Also, for the service business, many tasks are solved at the customers&#39; side by field staff. So, the ERP should support field operations, or it will be practically useless. The management team should be able to track employee load and performance right away.[/P][B][U]ROI calculation and inventory control[/U][/B]
[P]Services and repair may be hard to evaluate from the ROI standpoint. And this is what a good ERP system should provide to the business. The company should understand the cost of the repair or particular service in this specific case. [/P]
[P]To do so, the ERP system has to track the availability of the necessary spare parts, the delivery time based on the information from suppliers, etc. Moreover, the client can postpone the service like a repair or refuse to order all. If the employee had spent his or her working hours for the assessment, this also needs to be taken into account for cost calculation.[/P][B][U]Customization opportunities[/U][/B]
[P]Service businesses often use custom business processes. Therefore, there are no ERP solutions that can solve all tasks out of the box. Some customization will be required for maximum efficiency. And the software should support such customization. However, in reality, many ERP products do not provide a high level of flexibility, forcing companies to fit their existing business processes into the current software implementation, not adapt the solution to the business needs.[/P]
[P]This approach is rarely successful. When choosing an ERP for a service business, it is crucial to evaluate its flexibility and customization options. For example, the software should provide an opportunity to change its UX, add new modules, and integrate it with the existing business software.[/P][B][U]Easy-to-use interface[/U][/B]
[P]While it is a common perception of an ERP system as something &#39;complex&#39; that should be hard to use, the lighter and easier the UX is, the better results the software delivers. Overly complicated interfaces make workflows harder, generate more data entry mistakes, and demotivate employees working with a system. [/P]
[P]So, maximum efficiency must choose an ERP that is lightweight, easy to adopt, and use. The shorter the onboarding period for each user is, the faster they will reach the highest productivity level.[/P][B][U]Support[/U][/B]
[P]Quite often, business automation solutions vendors do not offer first-line support and training. This can significantly reduce the overall efficiency, extend the learning curve, and affect the implementation project timeline.[/P]
[P]In turn, if the vendor provides all the needed document forms for different scenarios from the service company lifecycle, it will make the adoption of the solution a lot easier. There are multiple features and business processes to automate, and it is great to get an opportunity to ask questions on how to do it faster and in a more efficient way.[/P][B][U]Localization[/U][/B]
[P]International software vendors often lack the proper support of local regulations. For example, in some Latin American countries, businesses are required to store all operations history. To send this data to regulators, the ERP should be integrated with the State Tax Service (facturacion electronica). Lots of well-known ERP solutions do not have this integration, while 1Ci:Drive does.[/P]";s:16:"DETAIL_TEXT_TYPE";s:4:"text";s:17:"~DETAIL_TEXT_TYPE";s:4:"text";s:11:"DATE_CREATE";s:17:"05.02.2021, 15:52";s:12:"~DATE_CREATE";s:17:"05.02.2021, 15:52";s:15:"DATE_PUBLISH_X1";s:19:"2021-02-05 15:51:00";s:16:"~DATE_PUBLISH_X1";s:19:"2021-02-05 15:51:00";s:12:"DATE_PUBLISH";s:17:"05.02.2021, 15:51";s:13:"~DATE_PUBLISH";s:17:"05.02.2021, 15:51";s:8:"KEYWORDS";N;s:9:"~KEYWORDS";N;s:14:"PUBLISH_STATUS";s:1:"P";s:15:"~PUBLISH_STATUS";s:1:"P";s:8:"ATRIBUTE";N;s:9:"~ATRIBUTE";N;s:10:"ATTACH_IMG";N;s:11:"~ATTACH_IMG";N;s:16:"ENABLE_TRACKBACK";s:1:"N";s:17:"~ENABLE_TRACKBACK";s:1:"N";s:15:"ENABLE_COMMENTS";s:1:"N";s:16:"~ENABLE_COMMENTS";s:1:"N";s:5:"VIEWS";s:3:"102";s:6:"~VIEWS";s:3:"102";s:12:"NUM_COMMENTS";s:1:"0";s:13:"~NUM_COMMENTS";s:1:"0";s:16:"NUM_COMMENTS_ALL";s:1:"0";s:17:"~NUM_COMMENTS_ALL";s:1:"0";s:4:"CODE";s:67:"how-to-choose-an-erp-for-service-companies-key-factors-and-features";s:5:"~CODE";s:67:"how-to-choose-an-erp-for-service-companies-key-factors-and-features";s:5:"MICRO";s:1:"N";s:6:"~MICRO";s:1:"N";s:14:"DATE_PUBLISHED";s:1:"Y";s:9:"urlToBlog";s:22:"/digital-intelligence/";s:9:"urlToPost";s:90:"/digital-intelligence/how-to-choose-an-erp-for-service-companies-key-factors-and-features/";s:11:"urlToAuthor";s:11:"/user/1148/";s:8:"arImages";a:1:{i:47;a:2:{s:5:"small";s:82:"/bitrix/components/bitrix/blog/show_file.php?fid=47&width=70&height=70&type=square";s:4:"full";s:74:"/bitrix/components/bitrix/blog/show_file.php?fid=47&width=1000&height=1000";}}s:13:"TEXT_FORMATED";s:301:"[P]Service and repair business has specific requirements that an ERP system should meet 